statement:
Let

\begin{align*}f(x) = \left\{
 \begin{array}{lr}
   e^{-x} & \text{if}\quad x < t\\
   2(x+1) & \text{if} \quad x \geq t
  \end{array}
\right.\end{align*}

Explain why there exists a number $t$ such that $f$ is continuous.

(Hint: apply the Intermediate Value Theorem to the function
$e^{-t}-2(t+1)$.)

sols:
The condition for $f$ to be continuous is

\begin{align*}
\lim_{x\rightarrow t^-} f(x) &= \lim_{x\rightarrow t^+} f(x)\\
e^{-t}&=2(t+1)\end{align*}

Since both piece of the function are continuous, we can use direct
substitution and find $t$. We must show there exists a solution to the
above equation. Equivalently we want to show that the following function
$g(t)$ has a zero

\begin{align*}
g(t)=e^{-t}-2(t+1)\end{align*}

Note that $g$ is continuous since it is constructed from continuous
functions. We aim to apply IVT. Observe

\begin{align*}
g(0)&=e^0-2<0\\
g(-1)&=e^1-2(-1+1)=e>0\end{align*}

Hence by the IVT there exists $c \in (-1,0)$ such that $g(c)=0$. At
$t=c$, we have $e^{-c} = 2(c+1)$. In turn, this means we have the two
one sided limits equalling each other and hence $f(x)$ will be
continuous by choosing $x=c$.
